# No `let` — use `const`

- Do **not** use `let` to declare variables. Always use `const`.
- Prefer immutable patterns: derive new values instead of reassigning.

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
let count = 0;
for (const x of items) {
  count += 1;
}

// ✅ GOOD
const count = items.length;
// or
const count = items.reduce((n) => n + 1, 0);
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
  console.log(arr[i]);
}

// ✅ GOOD
for (const [i, x] of arr.entries()) {
  console.log(x);
}
// or
arr.forEach((x, i) => { ... });
```

- If you truly need a mutable accumulator in a tight loop, wrap updates in a **block-scoped `const` object** (e.g. `const acc = { n: 0 }; acc.n += 1`) or use `reduce` / functional helpers instead of `let x = ...; x = ...`.

This matches the preference: **no `let` bindings in application code.**
